810 confusion key – advisory opinions and experience don’t solve 

Glasgow et al, Partner at Pillsbury Winthrop Shaw Pittman LLP’s Energy Practice, October 12 James A., Elina Teplinsky, and Stephen L. Markus, NUCLEAR EXPORT CONTROLS: A Comparative Analysis of National Regimes for the Control of Nuclear Materials, Components and Technology, http://www.nei.org/resourcesandstats/documentlibrary/newplants/whitepaper/nuclear-export-controls-a-comparative-analysis-of-national-regimes-for-the-control-of-nuclear-materials-components-and-technology

Despite the voluminous and complex nature of the DOC’s EAR, DOE’s Part 810 regulations are most often identified by U.S. exporters as the primary source of confusion, concern and delay. The Part 810 regulations, although concise, are based on vague statutory language that DOE’s Part 810 regulations do little to clarify. Consequently, U.S. companies – even those with considerable experience in exporting nuclear technology – often find the requirements of Part 810 confusing.
